  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 부들 채찍[蒲鞭] : '
    value: 한(漢)나라 유관(劉寬)이 백성을 다스리면서 아전이나 백성이 허물이 있으면, 다만 아프지 않은 부들 채찍[蒲鞭]을 써 벌하여 욕을 보일 따름이었다.
english:
  title: Spring Journey Along the Soyang River
  author: Lee Seonje
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Across the fertile plain spreads white mist like silk,
    and there Phoenix Mountain rises, propping up the azure sky.
    The Soyang River flows northward from the mountain,
    while Gwanghae, the old seat of government, nestles against the ridge.
    West of the mountain, south of its waters, lie the ruins of Yae—
    a land of gentle customs, ruled with the soft reed-whip of benevolence.
    The extravagance of old has faded with the ages,
    leaving only foundations where pavilions once stood by the clear stream.
    Yet Song Kong, in his devotion, raised it anew in mere days,
    and his architect's vision opened wide as this very pavilion.
    The roof-edge juts sharp against Phoenix Peak's flank,
    and now that the phoenix has departed, the empty mountain sings in pine-wind.
    I climb and gaze—ten thousand scenes come rushing down,
    their forms unchanging, as they were last year.
    But I return to find spring plum blossoms blooming again,
    and my restless heart grows weary with endless journeying east and west.
    Time flows on, indifferent to my plea,
    and fallen petals cling softly to moss turning green.
    Flower-fallen, moss-clung—what can one do?
    I lean upon the pillar, murmuring verse, unable to turn my head away.
    This year the spring drought comes doubly harsh,
    so I drink tea instead of wine to wet my lips.
    Seeds lie unsown as clouds break and scatter,
    and yellow dust swirls across the waiting fields.
    But the capital sends incense for rain-prayers,
    and farmers smile, pulling weeds with renewed hope.
    Wheat and barley stir back to life, new sprouts breaking through—
    shall this pavilion truly remain in silence forever?
    When autumn comes, I'll raise my cup to greet the bright moon,
    and never become merely a wanderer in this eastern land.
  footnotes:
    - The 'soft reed-whip' (蒲鞭) references the benevolent governance of Liu Kuan of the Han Dynasty, who used a non-painful reed whip to maintain order while showing compassion.
    - Phoenix Mountain (봉산) is the guardian peak of Chuncheon; the Soyang River is a major tributary in this region.
    - Song Kong likely refers to a contemporary official or scholar who commissioned the renovation of this pavilion.
